"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348372","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>A search by the Department’s Ministerial private offices and of the Ministerial correspondence database shows no discussions have been held, nor representations received in the past six months about Southend University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust's performance on accident and emergency waiting times.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348372/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T14:26:45.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348372/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348372/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Southend University Hospital: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent (a) discussions he has held and (b) representations he has received concerning Southend University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust's performance on A&E waiting times; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","1096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348373","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-08","<p>On 1 February 2015, ownership of the 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) transitioned to new providers. CRCs are now separate, private entities, contracted by the Department to provide specific services and as such are responsible for determining their budgets, staffing levels and staff salaries. As they are autonomous organisations, the MoJ no longer holds details of their budgeted annual expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of staffing, while CRCs are contractually required to have sufficient suitably qualified and competent staff, they are responsible for determining their own staffing levels and recruitment. No Chief Executives and only a small number of staff at Paybands A-D left their CRC posts during January 2015 while CRCs were still under public ownership. Since 1 February 2015, staffing has been a matter for CRC owners. The Department has not issued guidance to CRCs on recruitment.</p><p> </p><p>Following the transfer of ownership in February 2015, staff remuneration is now a matter for CRC providers. The salary of the Chief Executive of Essex CRC during the period 1 June 2014 to 31 January 2015 was in the range £90,000-£95,000. The governance structure of the Community Rehabilitation Companies did not include a position of Chairman during that period.</p><p> </p><p>The National Probation Service (NPS) may use agency staff to fill business-critical posts and essential frontline services where they can provide a fast, flexible and efficient way to obtain necessary skills that are not currently available in-house. The Department has issued a range of guidance (for example Probation Instructions) on the use of agency staff by the National Probation Service.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2015, official discussions continue with CRCs as part of the contract management process.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348373/answer",,,,,"1098 ; 691 ; 692 ; 693 ; 694 ; 695 ; 837","2015-06-08T15:04:03.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348373/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348373/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-03","Essex Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions (a) he, (b) Ministers of his Department and (c) officials of his Department have had with the Chief Executive of the Essex Community Rehabilitation Company; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","1097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348374","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-08","<p>On 1 February 2015, ownership of the 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) transitioned to new providers. CRCs are now separate, private entities, contracted by the Department to provide specific services and as such are responsible for determining their budgets, staffing levels and staff salaries. As they are autonomous organisations, the MoJ no longer holds details of their budgeted annual expenditure.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of staffing, while CRCs are contractually required to have sufficient suitably qualified and competent staff, they are responsible for determining their own staffing levels and recruitment. No Chief Executives and only a small number of staff at Paybands A-D left their CRC posts during January 2015 while CRCs were still under public ownership. Since 1 February 2015, staffing has been a matter for CRC owners. The Department has not issued guidance to CRCs on recruitment.</p><p> </p><p>Following the transfer of ownership in February 2015, staff remuneration is now a matter for CRC providers. The salary of the Chief Executive of Essex CRC during the period 1 June 2014 to 31 January 2015 was in the range £90,000-£95,000. The governance structure of the Community Rehabilitation Companies did not include a position of Chairman during that period.</p><p> </p><p>The National Probation Service (NPS) may use agency staff to fill business-critical posts and essential frontline services where they can provide a fast, flexible and efficient way to obtain necessary skills that are not currently available in-house. The Department has issued a range of guidance (for example Probation Instructions) on the use of agency staff by the National Probation Service.</p><p> </p><p>Since January 2015, official discussions continue with CRCs as part of the contract management process.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial meetings with external organisations are published quarterly.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348374/answer",,,,,"1097 ; 691 ; 692 ; 693 ; 694 ; 695 ; 837","2015-06-08T15:04:03.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348374/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348374/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-06-03","Essex Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what guidance on recruitment of officials (a) he, (b) Ministers of his Department and (c) officials of his Department (i) have issued since January 2015 and (ii) plan to issue within the next six months to Essex Community Rehabilitation Company; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","1098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348375","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-29","<p>Previous Governments ran out of parliamentary time to bring forward the necessary legislation to ratify the 1954 Hague Convention on the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict and accede to its two Protocols.</p><p> </p><p>This Government’s priority is to bring forward legislation to allow this at the first opportunity.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348375/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-29T11:37:46.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348375/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348375/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-06-03","UN Convention for Protection of Cultural Property in Event of Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the UK has not ratified the 1954 Hague Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property in the Event of Armed Conflict; and whether he plans to ratify that treaty.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","1024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348376","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>The price paid by National Health Service trusts for devices varies significantly, as does, correspondingly, the cost passed onto the NHS. Analysis indicates the percentage difference between the lower and highest prices for duel chamber implantable defibrillators to be in the region of 90% and cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators 75%.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348376/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-11T10:36:39.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348376/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348376/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Defibrillators: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what variation there is in (a) prices paid by NHS trusts for implantable defibrillators and cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators and (b) the costs for such devices that trusts pass back to NHS England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348377","Department of Health","false","2015-06-08","<p>Guidance will be made available to local authority trading standards officers, or in the case of Northern Ireland, environmental health officers. It will be developed with the relevant bodies responsible and made publically available before the Standardised Packaging of Tobacco Products Regulations 2015 come into force.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348377/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T15:28:25.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348377/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348377/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Tobacco: Packaging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what preparations his Department is making for the commencement of the Standardised Packaging of Tobacco Products Regulations 2015 on 20 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","1058"
