"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348401","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Government has made no estimate of the cost of electrifying the Gospel Oak to Barking railway line. Network Rail will provide an estimate following formal sign-off of stage 3 of the Governance for Railway Investment Projects (‘GRIP’) process.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport has allocated £90 million towards the project (2013 prices).</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348401/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T11:04:06.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348401/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348401/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-03","Gospel Oak-Barking Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost of electrifying the Gospel Oak to Barking railway line; and what contribution his Department plans to make to that project.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348402","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>We are deeply concerned about the destruction of cultural heritage in Syria and Iraq, including the specific threat to Palmyra. The United Kingdom co-sponsored both UN Security Council Resolution 2199 (2015), which condemns the destruction of cultural heritage and requires member states to take measures to prevent the trade in looted antiquities, and UN General Assembly Resolution A/RES/69/281 (28 May 2015), which expresses the outrage of the global community at attacks on cultural heritage as a tactic of war to spread terror and hatred. My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs (Mr Hammond) discussed the protection of cultural heritage with his counterparts at the meeting of the Global Anti-ISIL Coalition Small Group in Paris on 2 June, at which UNESCO Director-General Ms Irina Bokova was present. Ultimately the only way of safeguarding these valuable historic sites is by defeating ISIL and establishing a lasting peace in both Syria and Iraq.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348402/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T12:10:58.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348402/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348402/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-03","Armed Conflict: Cultural Heritage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans he has to raise at (a) the UN and (b) UNESCO (i) the threat of destruction to the city of Palmyra in Syria from ISIS and (ii) ways in which the international community can intervene to protect valuable historical sites.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348403","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-08","<p>The House recognises the sacrifice of those killed in the service of their country in a range of ways. This includes honouring all those who have fallen by observing a period of silence when sitting on Armistice Day. The Prime Minister also remains committed to continuing to pay tribute to those who have died and been named by the Ministry of Defence. What individual Members are allowed to do on the floor of the House is largely a matter of practice and convention under the control of Mr Speaker. The Government has no plans to change the current procedures but we will keep it under review.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348403/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T16:40:00.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348403/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348403/answer",,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-03","House of Commons: Standing Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if he will bring forward proposals to amend the standing orders of the House to allow hon. Members to read out the names of fallen soldiers on the floor of the House.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348404","Leader of the House","false","2015-06-08","<p>There are no plans to bring forward proposals to change the rules for the election of the Speaker.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348404/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T16:40:41.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348404/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348404/answer",,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2015-06-03","Speaker: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, whether he plans to bring forward proposals to change the rules for the election of the Speaker.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348405","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-12","<p>The Hunting Act came into force on 18 February 2005. Between 2005 and 2014 (the latest year for which official figures are available), a total of 590 individuals were prosecuted for a range of offences under the Hunting Act. Of these, 378 were found guilty.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348405/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-12T13:52:07.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348405/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348405/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-03","Hunting Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness with which the Hunting Act 2004 has been implemented.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348406","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 2 June 2015 to Question 428 to the hon. Member for St Helens North (Conor McGinn).</p><p>In addition, it is likely that other organisations have benefited from LIBOR funds distributed by other Government Departments. However this information could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348406/answer","HOC 979.doc ; 20150601-40M Veterans Accommodation Fund[1].doc HOC979.doc ; 20150601-35M LIBOR Fund(2).xls HL 115.xls HOC 979.xls","HOC 979.doc ; 20150601-40M Veterans Accommodation Fund[1].doc HOC979.doc ; 20150601-35M LIBOR Fund(2).xls HL 115.xls HOC 979.xls","Hansard Extract 2 June 2015 ; Veterans Accomoation Fund ; Libor Fund ","Hansard Extract 2 June 2015 ; Veterans Accomoation Fund ; Libor Fund ",,"2015-06-09T15:27:14.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348406/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348406/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-03","Armed Forces Covenant: Wirral South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what organisations in Wirral South constituency have received funding from the Libor fund; and how much each such organisation has received.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348407","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) handles 50 million calls a year from customers. The department is working hard to improve its performance. The percentage of calls handled will fluctuate annually and quarterly and is directly affected by customer demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC has taken a number of steps including the introduction of a new telephony platform that will improve performance in the longer term. HMRC has recruited more than 2,000 staff to its customer service teams and is expanding the resource available at evenings and weekends when many customers choose to call. They have also launched an online service for Tax Credit customers that will enable them to renew their claims without calling at all and, as in previous years, are moving up to 1,500 extra staff from across the department to support the Tax Credits peak in demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348407/answer",,,,,"976","2015-06-08T15:12:50.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348407/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348407/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-03","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 4, what the reason was for the size of the reduction in the percentage of calls handled by HM Revenue and Customs contact centres within five minutes in the first two quarters of 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348408","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-08","<p>The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) is responsible for determining the efficient cost of Network Rail’s CP5 enhancement schemes, not the Department for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>As explained in my previous response to the Honourable Member for Nottingham South, the ORR publishes quarterly updates on the enhancements cost adjustment mechanism (ECAM) process. This includes information about efficiencies identified on specific schemes through the ECAM process. For example, the ORR recently published ECAM findings on Reading Station area redevelopment, Great Western electrification and Midland Main Line electrification on its website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://orr.gov.uk/what-and-how-we-regulate/regulation-of-network-rail/how-we-regulate-network-rail/control-period-5-cp5/cp5-delivery-plan" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/what-and-how-we-regulate/regulation-of-network-rail/how-we-regulate-network-rail/control-period-5-cp5/cp5-delivery-plan</a>.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348408/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T11:12:42.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348408/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348408/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-03","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 161, what estimate his Department has made of the efficient cost of those Control Period 5 projects that have completed the enhancement cost adjustment mechanism process; and what the estimated cost was of those projects before they began that process.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348409","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) handles 50 million calls a year from customers. The department is working hard to improve its performance. The percentage of calls handled will fluctuate annually and quarterly and is directly affected by customer demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC has taken a number of steps including the introduction of a new telephony platform that will improve performance in the longer term. HMRC has recruited more than 2,000 staff to its customer service teams and is expanding the resource available at evenings and weekends when many customers choose to call. They have also launched an online service for Tax Credit customers that will enable them to renew their claims without calling at all and, as in previous years, are moving up to 1,500 extra staff from across the department to support the Tax Credits peak in demand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348409/answer",,,,,"984","2015-06-08T15:12:50.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348409/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348409/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-03","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 4, what steps he is taking to increase the proportion of calls handled by HM Revenue and Customs' Contact Centre within five minutes.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348410","Department for Education","false","2015-06-08","<p>We will publish draft regulations which define coasting schools in time to allow for parliamentary scrutiny.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We will also consult more widely on this definition in the summer.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348410/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T15:35:46.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348410/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348410/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-03","Education and Adoption Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish draft regulations defining coasting before the Second Reading of the Education and Adoption Bill.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","1006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348411","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-08","<p>I can confirm that I have placed copies of the Department’s Level Crossing Reform Action Plan in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348411/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T11:44:04.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348411/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348411/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-03","Level Crossings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place in the Library a copy of the Level Crossing Reform Action Plan.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","1008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348412","Department of Health","false","2015-06-10","<p>The commissioning intentions state NHS England will look at excluded devices and some drugs. The process began with implantable cardiac devices, bone anchored hearing devices and transcatheter aortic valve implantation, and proceeded to cover all excluded devices.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348412/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:53:16.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348412/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348412/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Medical Equipment: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England plans to establish reference prices for medical devices beyond those named in the Commissioning Intentions for 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348413","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>When establishing the suggested average prices the Complex Invasive Cardiology - Clinical Reference Group lead and clinical representatives were involved in supporting and understanding the need for average prices for implantable defibrillators and cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348413/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-11T10:43:04.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348413/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348413/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Defibrillators: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which National Clinical Directors and Clinical Reference Groups have been involved in establishing best value prices and reference prices for implantable defibrillators and cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348414","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>The costs incurred by National Health Service trusts for high cost devices such as implantable and cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators are re-charged to NHS England on a pass-through basis, i.e. the re-charge equals the cost invoiced by the supplier of the device. Correspondingly the financial impact of high cost device purchases are cost-neutral to NHS trusts and do not impact on their income and expenditure position.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, NHS England specialised commissioning is currently supporting NHS trusts with information on European Union compliant procurement frameworks that offer better value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348414/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-11T10:54:37.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348414/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348414/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Medical Equipment: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what modelling NHS England has done to determine (a) the effects of trends in NHS trusts' income on (i) provision of (A) implantable defibrillators, (B) cardiac resynchronisation defibrillators and (C) other high cost devices and (ii) service viability and (b) the effects of provision of high cost devices on the future financial positions of trusts.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348415","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-08","<p /> <p>We will set out our policy design in due course.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348415/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T10:07:06.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348415/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348415/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-03","Employment and Support Allowance: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is his policy that the proposed legislation requiring young people to earn or learn will extend to existing claimants of employment and support allowance under the age of 21.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","1030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348416","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Neither the Department nor NHS England has made any assessment of the cost of the provision of fitness for work certificates.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348416/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-11T10:50:06.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348416/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348416/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to NHS England of the provision of fitness for work certificates as required by the Department for Work and Pensions in the period 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348417","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Trusts are obliged to charge the National Health Service the cost of the implantable devices on a pass through basis, i.e. the cost invoiced by the supplier of the device. The average prices have been issued to commissioners to help them assess value for money on device expenditure and identify potential areas for future efficiency improvements. NHS England’s current approach is not to impose a ceiling price however; we will be working closely with providers where they are not taking advantage of current market rates for devices.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348417/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-11T10:45:13.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348417/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348417/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Medical Equipment: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether NHS England plans to establish reference prices as ceiling prices above which trusts will not be reimbursed.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","1023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348418","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-01","<p>The government committed to providing free, impartial guidance through Pension Wise, to help people make informed and confident decisions about how they use their defined contribution pension savings in retirement. It is available online, via the telephone and face to face.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As of 6 April – the date on which the new pension flexibilities commenced – Pension Wise had handled more than 3,600 calls since the opening of the contact centre in late March. Nearly 1400 people had booked a telephone guidance appointment with the Pensions Advisory Service, while nearly 380 people had booked a face to face appointment with Citizens Advice. Citizens Advice does not provide Pension Wise guidance over the phone.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on Pension Wise service usage since 6 April will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Pension Wise recommends that users take their time to prepare and gather relevant information before their guidance session, if they have not already done so by the time of booking their appointment; this can normally take around 2 weeks. The government estimates that, on average, face to face appointments take place within 9 days of booking.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348418/answer",,,,,"HL231 ; HL232","2015-07-01T15:54:22.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348418/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348418/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-03","Pensions: Advisory Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people sought telephone advice from The Pensions Advisory Service in (1) April following the commencement of the Pensions Schemes Act 2015, and (2) May.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348419","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-01","<p>The government committed to providing free, impartial guidance through Pension Wise, to help people make informed and confident decisions about how they use their defined contribution pension savings in retirement. It is available online, via the telephone and face to face.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As of 6 April – the date on which the new pension flexibilities commenced – Pension Wise had handled more than 3,600 calls since the opening of the contact centre in late March. Nearly 1400 people had booked a telephone guidance appointment with the Pensions Advisory Service, while nearly 380 people had booked a face to face appointment with Citizens Advice. Citizens Advice does not provide Pension Wise guidance over the phone.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on Pension Wise service usage since 6 April will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Pension Wise recommends that users take their time to prepare and gather relevant information before their guidance session, if they have not already done so by the time of booking their appointment; this can normally take around 2 weeks. The government estimates that, on average, face to face appointments take place within 9 days of booking.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348419/answer",,,,,"HL230 ; HL232","2015-07-01T15:54:22.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348419/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348419/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-03","Pensions: Advisory Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people sought (1) telephone advice, and (2) an in-person interview, with Citizens Advice in (a) April following the commencement of the Pensions Schemes Act 2015, and (b) May.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348420","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-01","<p>The government committed to providing free, impartial guidance through Pension Wise, to help people make informed and confident decisions about how they use their defined contribution pension savings in retirement. It is available online, via the telephone and face to face.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As of 6 April – the date on which the new pension flexibilities commenced – Pension Wise had handled more than 3,600 calls since the opening of the contact centre in late March. Nearly 1400 people had booked a telephone guidance appointment with the Pensions Advisory Service, while nearly 380 people had booked a face to face appointment with Citizens Advice. Citizens Advice does not provide Pension Wise guidance over the phone.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on Pension Wise service usage since 6 April will be published in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Pension Wise recommends that users take their time to prepare and gather relevant information before their guidance session, if they have not already done so by the time of booking their appointment; this can normally take around 2 weeks. The government estimates that, on average, face to face appointments take place within 9 days of booking.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348420/answer",,,,,"HL230 ; HL231","2015-07-01T15:54:22.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348420/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348420/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-03","Citizens Advice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the current waiting time for an in-person interview with Citizens Advice.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348421","Department of Health","false","2015-06-15","<p>Tackling obesity is one of our major priorities. Progress has been made in recent years, but we know we have much further to go and we will put forward our plans in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348421/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-15T11:31:24.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348421/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348421/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Obesity: Cancer","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to tackle obesity as a cause of cancer deaths.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348422","Department of Health","false","2015-06-16","<p>Nivolumab for previously treated locally advanced or metastatic non-small cell lung cancer was referred to the National Institute for Care Excellence (NICE) in March 2015. The development of the appraisal is expected to start shortly, and NICE is anticipating final guidance to be issued in May 2016.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348422/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-16T14:35:32.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348422/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348422/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","Nivolumab","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to improve lung cancer therapy available on the NHS in the light of the recent trial of Nivolumab.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423","Department of Health","true","2015-06-17","<p>On 1 June 2015, Monitor published <em>Improving GP Services: Commissioners and Patient Choice</em>, which included the findings of a nationally representative survey conducted by Ipsos Mori.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The report noted a high level of satisfaction with general practice overall. It found that 81% of patients were satisfied with their general practitioner (GP) practice, while only 10% were dissatisfied.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Monitor’s report found that, after location, patients most value the ease of getting an appointment when choosing a GP practice. In order to improve access for patients, the Government has invested £175 million over two years through the Prime Minister’s GP Access Fund. This is testing improved and innovative access to GP services through longer opening hours, such as at evenings and weekends, but also different ways of accessing services, for example the use of Skype consultations. Altogether, there are now 57 schemes covering over 2,500 practices, meaning that over 18 million patients are expected to benefit from improved access and transformational change at local level by March 2016.</p><p>Additionally, the Primary Care Infrastructure Fund is investing £1 billion<ins class="ministerial">, including</ins> <del class="ministerial">and</del> £25 million as part of the Prime Minister’s GP Access Fund, over four years to improve premises and information technology, which will also improve access.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-17T13:19:17.147Z","2015-06-19T11:00:07.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423/answer",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423/answer/previousversion/5697","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348423/answer/previousversion/5697",,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-03","General Practitioners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the results of a survey on behalf of Monitor, which found that one in ten people are dissatisfied with their general practitioner surgery.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348424","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Higher Education Academy (HEA) report ‘<em>Grade Point Average: Report of the GPA pilot project 2013-14’, </em>published on 28 May 2015, was a result of a review undertaken by HEA’s national Grade Point Average Advisory Group. The Department has noted the report. However, higher education institutions with degree awarding powers are responsible for their own academic awards. It is a matter for institutions to consider the recommendation as independent and autonomous bodies.</p><p><br></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348424/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T11:13:08.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348424/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348424/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-03","Universities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the report by the Higher Education Academy recommending that United Kingdom universities should adopt the grade point average system.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348425","Home Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>We work closely with local authorities to ensure that immigration decisions in cases receiving local authority support are made as quickly as possible. The No Recourse to Public Funds Connect database provides an expedited route into the Home Office for local authorities on individual cases, so that these can be dealt with as quickly as possible. Where migrants granted leave to remain on family grounds show that they are destitute or that there are exceptional circumstances, they are given recourse to public funds.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348425/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:30:27.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348425/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348425/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-03","Immigrants: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to reimburse local authorities for the costs falling to them in caring for children from families with no recourse to public funds as they attempt to regulate their immigration status, in the light of the report by the Centre on Migration, Policy and Society <i>Safeguarding Children From Destitution</i>; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348426","Department for Education","false","2015-06-17","<p>The Department for Education is clear about how local authorities should support 16 and 17 year-olds presenting as homeless. The report from the Children’s Society, ‘Getting the house in order’ reminds local authorities to ensure that under-18s who are homeless receive the help they need. The government has no current plans to legislate on this issue, but we are taking action to ensure that all homeless people have access to the help that they need: we have invested £500 million in homelessness services, including funding for the development of the ‘Youth accommodation pathway’ service model. This is designed to support all young people remain in the family home where it is safe to do so, and offer tailored support options for those that cannot remain in the family home, including supported accommodation as a starting point for 16- to 17-year-olds.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>With regard to 16- to 17-year-old care leavers, revised statutory guidance was issued to local authorities in 2010, setting out how they can better meet the needs of this group. It makes clear that local authorities should work pro-actively with young people and their families to identify and resolve issues which have led them to become homeless. The guidance also underlines the importance of effective agency collaboration between Children’s Services and Housing Services.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The guidance reminds Housing Services that applicants cannot be considered to have become homeless intentionally if they fail to take up an offer of accommodation; the guidance says that homelessness can only be deemed to be ‘intentional’ where the applicant has ceased to occupy accommodation that it would have been reasonable for him or her to continue to occupy. Local authorities that do not follow these procedures are open to legal challenge. The full statutory guidance on the provision of accommodation for 16- to 17-year-olds who may be homeless or require accommodation can be accessed on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Since 2013, Ofsted inspections of local authorities’ children’s social care services have included a separate sub-judgement on care leavers, which includes an assessment of whether the local authority is ensuring that care leavers have access to suitable accommodation. Where Ofsted judges that a local authority’s social care services are inadequate, the department may intervene to secure necessary improvements in the quality of care that is provided.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348426/answer",,,,,"HL239 ; HL240","2015-06-17T13:22:49.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348426/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348426/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-03","Homelessness: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that 16 and 17 year-olds presenting as homeless receive a seamless joint assessment from Children's Services and Housing Services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL238"
