Data for those in the second table gives a summary of those who left teaching either when on, or after completing, the Teach First Leadership Development Programme. This includes all those who have completed the Teach First programme since the first cohort in 2003. The data also includes those who have left more than once – for example an individual who leaves the profession in one year, returned, and then left the profession once more – for example someone taking career breaks and/or maternity leave.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Please see detailed tables in Appendix 1 (separate excel file) for data on Teach First teachers in each parliamentary constituency that began teaching in each of the last five years as well as those that left the teaching profession in each of the last five years.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348024/answer","853  Appendix- teach first teachers entering and leaving B.xlsx","853  Appendix- teach first teachers entering and leaving B.xlsx","Teach First teachers entering and leaving by PC","Teach First teachers entering and leaving by PC",,"2015-06-10T11:49:39.07Z","2015-07-08T14:43:46.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348024/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348024/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348024/answer/previousversion/3497","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348024/answer/previousversion/3497","853  Appendix- teach first teachers entering and leaving.xlsx","Teach first teachers entering and leaving by PC","60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Teachers: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many Teach First teachers in each (a) subject and (b) parliamentary constituency (i) began teaching and (ii) left the teaching profession in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348025","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The pay and conditions of school support staff is determined locally. Schools should have flexibility over pay and conditions and the freedom to organise staff and resources in a way that reflects local priorities and needs.</p><p> </p><p>It is not the policy of this government to reinstate the School Support Staff Negotiating Body (SSSNB). The SSSNB was abolished by the previous government in 2010.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348025/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T11:38:36.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348025/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348025/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","School Support Staff Negotiating Body","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will reinstate the School Support Staff Negotiating Body.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348026","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The Secretary of State for Education has not made an assessment of the number of teaching assistants who are performing a full teaching role in schools in England.</p><p>The Education (Specified Work) (England) Regulations 2012 set out the specific circumstances in which someone employed in a maintained school other than a qualified teacher can teach; and where teaching assistants can be used to cover teacher absence. These regulations state that teaching assistants may only carry out specified teaching work where they are assisting or supporting the work of a qualified teacher in the school and are under the direction and supervision of a qualified teacher as arranged by the headteacher. This ensures that a teacher continues to provide the leading contribution.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348026/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T11:40:33.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348026/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348026/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Classroom Assistants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the number of teaching assistants who are performing a full teaching role in schools in England.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348027","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The salaries of teaching assistants in all state-funded schools are determined locally; factors such as geographical region, school phase, teaching assistants’ relevant experience, level of responsibilities and local labour market conditions will all influence the salary level. The latest available information in the following table does not take any of these factors into account.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Average annual salary of teaching assistants in state-funded schools in England, November 2013</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>Average (mean) salary of full and part-time teaching assistants</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of full and part-time teaching assistants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Local authority maintained schools</p></td><td><p>£16,300</p></td><td><p>259,528</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Academy schools</p></td><td><p>£16,200</p></td><td><p>59,536</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Free schools</p></td><td><p>£16,100</p></td><td><p>575</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All schools</strong></p></td><td><p>£16,300</p></td><td><p>319,733</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: School Workforce Census, November 2013</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><p>The average salary for each school type has been calculated using the total number of full and part-time teaching assistants for whom salary data was available in those schools.</p><p>University Technical Colleges and Studio schools are only included in the all school figures.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13% (48,400) of teaching assistants have been excluded as their full time equivalent salary is outside the range £12,000- £25,000.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348027/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:38:00.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348027/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348027/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Classroom Assistants: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average salary is for teaching assistants in (a) state maintained schools, (b) free schools and (c) academy schools.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348028","Department for Education","false","2015-06-09","<p>The department supports the removal of asbestos from schools, where it is safe and appropriate to do so, through its capital funding schemes.</p><p> </p><p>We are spending £1.4 billion to improve the condition of the school estate in financial year 2015 to 2016. The majority of this £1.4 billion (over £950 million) goes directly to schools and those responsible for them, and it is for them to decide how to use this funding to address their needs, including to manage and remove asbestos where appropriate. The legal responsibility for managing asbestos in schools rests with local authorities, academy trusts, governing bodies and other duty holders and so we rightly provide them with the flexibility to use their funding to carry out this duty.</p><p> </p><p>The remainder of the £1.4 billion goes through the Condition Improvement Fund (CIF), which provides more than £430 million to address the condition needs of academies in small multi-academy trusts and single academy trusts, as well as sixth-form colleges. This includes funding projects that remove asbestos from schools, as well as projects that will encapsulate asbestos, rather than removing it.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, where schools are being refurbished or rebuilt by the department as part of the Priority School Building Programmes, through which we will invest around £4bn, the costs of any asbestos management work, including removing it – where that is appropriate – are being met by the department. We do not make a specific allowance for asbestos works in a scheme. This is managed alongside other site risks. We allow 17% of the capital cost of a scheme for these risks and a central contingency is held for exceptional cases. This spending is often incorporated into the wider costs associated with demolition or refurbishment work.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348028/answer",,,,,"710","2015-06-09T16:15:07.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348028/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348028/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Schools: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department will spend to remove asbestos from primary and secondary schools in the next financial year.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348029","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The information requested is not collected by the Department for Education.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348029/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T11:25:26.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348029/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348029/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Classroom Assistants: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the number of hours outside contracted hours worked by teaching assistants in (a) Sheffield and (b) England over the last three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348030","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The information requested is not collected by the Department for Education.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348030/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T11:37:27.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348030/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348030/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Teachers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what records her Department keeps on the number of job applications for each advertised teaching position.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348031","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The Department for Education uses the Teacher Supply Model (TSM) to estimate the demand for the number of qualified teachers in active service within state-funded schools in England each year using a range of assumptions including projections for the numbers of pupils in schools and the number of teachers expected to leave the sector.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To estimate the demand for teachers for specific secondary subjects, the TSM uses the latest data on secondary subject take-up, defined by hours taught, and projected pupil numbers at Key Stages 3 to 5. It also takes into account the different age and gender demographics of teachers for different subjects (which affect the likelihood of teachers of different subjects leaving the profession or retiring) and assumptions on the impacts of subject-specific policy changes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department published the TSM’s estimate of teacher demand in part 1 of the TSM used to determine 2015/16 ITT allocations, along with a user guide explaining the methodology in detail, at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model</a></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348031/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:23:24.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348031/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348031/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how her Department assesses demand for teachers in each subject area.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348032","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The Department for Education uses the Teacher Supply Model (TSM) to estimate the demand for the number of qualified teachers in active service within state-funded schools in England. To estimate the demand for teachers in specific subjects (including STEM), the TSM uses the latest data on secondary subject take-up and projected pupil numbers at Key Stages 3 to 5. It also accounts for the different age and gender demographics of the teacher stock in each subject (which affect the likelihood of teachers leaving the stock or retiring). We monitor the current supply of teachers using the annual School Workforce Census. The current supply and future demand for qualified teachers as estimated by the 2015/16 TSM along with a user guide explaining the methodology in detail is published online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The department also monitors the current supply of teachers (including STEM teachers) using data on full-time classroom teacher vacancies in secondary schools by subject. In 2013, the vacancy rate was 1.1% for mathematics, 1.0% for the sciences, 0.6% for design and technology, and 1.0% for information technology. Data on vacancies for other subjects and historical vacancy rates for STEM subjects are available in Table 15 in the main tables of the school workforce statistical first release, published online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2013" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2013</a></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348032/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:27:10.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348032/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348032/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","STEM Subjects: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of levels of supply and demand for qualified teachers in STEM subjects.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348033","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348033/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T15:33:34.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348033/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348033/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-02","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many qualified STEM teachers there are per (a) primary and (b) secondary school pupil in each parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348034","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-08","<p>It is for Ofgem, working with the Health and Safety Executive, to define the gas mains replacement programme. If Ofgem were to review this programme and to request DECC to enable changes, we would assess any relevant impacts at that time.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348034/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T13:27:35.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348034/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348034/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-02","Natural Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of OFGEM's plans to re-examine the current gas mains replacement programme on long term stability of gas supply in the UK.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348035","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-10","<p /> <p>Figures are not available on the numbers of apprenticeships taken up with the same or different employer.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 attached shows the number of apprenticeship starts by individuals aged 19-64 who were in receipt of a DWP benefit in the 6 months prior to starting their learning in the 2010/11, 2011/12 and 2012/13 academic years (August – July). Statistics are only available for these academic years.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012/13, 45,800 individuals started an apprenticeship who were previously in the receipt of Jobseeker’s Allowance or in the Employment and Support Allowance Work Related Activity Group in the 6 months prior to starting their learning. This is an increase from 42,900 in 2011/12 and 33,500 in 2010/11.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348035/answer","Table 1 Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefits before training by Benefit Type, Level and Academic Year.doc","Table 1 Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefits before training by Benefit Type, Level and Academic Year.doc","Table 1: Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefi","Table 1: Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefi","776","2015-06-10T16:06:08.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348035/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348035/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many apprenticeship places were taken up by people (a) already in employment with the same employer, (b) already in employment with a new employer and (c) who were previously unemployed in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348036","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-06-10","<p>Figures are not available on the numbers of apprenticeships taken up with the same or different employer.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 attached shows the number of apprenticeship starts by individuals aged 19-64 who were in receipt of a DWP benefit in the 6 months prior to starting their learning in the 2010/11, 2011/12 and 2012/13 academic years (August – July). Statistics are only available for these academic years.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012/13, 45,800 individuals started an apprenticeship who were previously in the receipt of Jobseeker’s Allowance or in the Employment and Support Allowance Work Related Activity Group in the 6 months prior to starting their learning. This is an increase from 42,900 in 2011/12 and 33,500 in 2010/11.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348036/answer","Table 1 Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefits before training by Benefit Type, Level and Academic Year.doc","Table 1 Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefits before training by Benefit Type, Level and Academic Year.doc","Table 1: Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefi","Table 1: Apprentices aged 19-64 who claimed benefi","775","2015-06-10T16:06:09.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348036/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348036/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-06-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of those previously unemployed found work as a result of an apprenticeship in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","776"
