"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348187","Department of Health","false","2015-06-08","<p>Information is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information on the mean and median duration to (i) assessment, (ii) treatment and (iii) departure, in minutes, in the accident and emergency (A&amp;E) department for University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust for each year since 2009-10 is shown in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348187/answer","Average A&E waiting times data.xlsx","Average A&E waiting times data.xlsx","University Hospital Birmingham FT 2009-10 A&E Data","University Hospital Birmingham FT 2009-10 A&E Data",,"2015-06-08T11:06:20.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348187/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348187/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-02","Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time at the Accident and Emergency Unit of the Queen Elizabeth Hospital was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348188","Department of Health","false","2015-06-08","<p>Latest data for week ending 31 May 2015 showed that University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust met the operational standard of at least 95% of patients being admitted, transferred or discharged within four hours of arrival at an accident and emergency department, with performance at 95.8%. In 2014/15 as a whole 94.8% of patients were admitted, treated or discharged within four hours.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348188/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T15:30:30.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348188/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348188/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-02","Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham: Accident and Emergency Departments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of accident and emergency services at the Queen Elizabeth Hospital in Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348189","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-08","<p>653 households were placed in temporary accommodation by Southwark council in 2014. No data is held centrally on the types of households being placed in temporary accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>In the calendar year 2014, 449 households left temporary accommodation in Southwark as a result of accepting an offer of accommodation, although no figures are held centrally as to whether the accommodation offered was within the Borough.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348189/answer",,,,,"802 ; 803 ; 804","2015-06-08T15:10:27.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348189/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/348189/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-06-02","Temporary Accommodation: Southwark","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) single-headed households, (b) households with children, (c) households with pensioners, (d) households where one or more person is employed and (e) households with a disabled member were placed in temporary accommodation by the London Borough of Southwark in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","801"
