 ; HL164 ; HL167","2015-06-09T13:31:13.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347619/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347619/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Health Services: Staffordshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the recommendations of the Staffordshire Distressed Health Economy report by KPMG have been subject to public consultation and scrutiny.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347620","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>One of the key functions of the Health and Wellbeing Boards is to promote greater integration and partnership, including joint commissioning, so it is for them to decide how they collaborate to achieve the best outcomes for their population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Commissioning Congress has been set up in Staffordshire to bring together both clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and local authority commissioners. The six CCGs have a line of accountability to Health and Wellbeing Boards to deliver the health and wellbeing strategies as part of the transformation programme. The Congress will lead the Transformation Strategy which will drive the service redesign of the Staffordshire Health and Social Care economy to secure financially and clinically sustainable services in the long term. The Congress will engage with local providers in developing these plans to ensure that there is a single five-year plan for the local health economy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In order to produce a single plan there are a number of steps have to be taken, following on from the work to date by KPMG. These include the consideration of strategic plans, consultations on possible reforms and the implementation of recommendations flowing from this. To release information ahead of these steps could possibly prejudice the outcome. There will be a full public consultation on the resulting plans during the autumn of 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has identified the Staffordshire CCGs as high risk, and as such is monitoring their performance on a monthly basis with a full quarterly review of finance and performance. NHS England increases the intensity of performance reviews where there are significant shortfalls, and this includes weekly meetings with CCGs where appropriate.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347620/answer",,,,,"HL162 ; HL163 ; HL167","2015-06-09T13:31:14.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347620/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347620/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Clinical Commissioning Groups: Staffordshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the recommendations of the Staffordshire Distressed Health Economy report by KPMG have been discussed in open session meetings of the six Clinical Commissioning Groups in Staffordshire.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347621","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Leadership and collaborative working relationships are critical factors in securing sustainable services in any local health economy. The Commissioning Congress has been set up to bring together both clinical commissioning groups and local authority commissioners. The Congress will engage with local providers in developing plans to secure clinically and financially sustainable services in the long term. The priority for all involved is ensuring a viable set of services which will be both clinically and financially sustainable in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347621/answer",,,,,"HL166","2015-06-11T14:52:48.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347621/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347621/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Health Services: Staffordshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the conclusion of the Staffordshire Distressed Health Economy report by KPMG that there is an "oppressive culture" across Staffordshire with a system in "perpetual crisis mode".","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347622","Department of Health","false","2015-06-11","<p>Leadership and collaborative working relationships are critical factors in securing sustainable services in any local health economy. The Commissioning Congress has been set up to bring together both clinical commissioning groups and local authority commissioners. The Congress will engage with local providers in developing plans to secure clinically and financially sustainable services in the long term. The priority for all involved is ensuring a viable set of services which will be both clinically and financially sustainable in the future.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347622/answer",,,,,"HL165","2015-06-11T14:52:48.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347622/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347622/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Health Services: Staffordshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure the change of the senior leadership in Staffordshire health services in the light of the criticism made in the Staffordshire Distressed Health Economy report by KPMG.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347623","Department of Health","false","2015-06-09","<p>One of the key functions of the Health and Wellbeing Boards is to promote greater integration and partnership, including joint commissioning, so it is for them to decide how they collaborate to achieve the best outcomes for their population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Commissioning Congress has been set up in Staffordshire to bring together both clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and local authority commissioners. The six CCGs have a line of accountability to Health and Wellbeing Boards to deliver the health and wellbeing strategies as part of the transformation programme. The Congress will lead the Transformation Strategy which will drive the service redesign of the Staffordshire Health and Social Care economy to secure financially and clinically sustainable services in the long term. The Congress will engage with local providers in developing these plans to ensure that there is a single five-year plan for the local health economy.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In order to produce a single plan there are a number of steps have to be taken, following on from the work to date by KPMG. These include the consideration of strategic plans, consultations on possible reforms and the implementation of recommendations flowing from this. To release information ahead of these steps could possibly prejudice the outcome. There will be a full public consultation on the resulting plans during the autumn of 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has identified the Staffordshire CCGs as high risk, and as such is monitoring their performance on a monthly basis with a full quarterly review of finance and performance. NHS England increases the intensity of performance reviews where there are significant shortfalls, and this includes weekly meetings with CCGs where appropriate.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347623/answer",,,,,"HL162 ; HL163 ; HL164","2015-06-09T13:31:14.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347623/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347623/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-06-01","Health Services: Staffordshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of NHS England's stewardship and oversight of the Staffordshire local health economy; and what criteria they have used to make this assessment.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347624","Department for Education","false","2015-06-10","<p>The government is committed to tackling violence against women and girls (VAWG). We are helping to end violence at home and abroad by allowing women to check their partner’s criminal history, introducing domestic violence protection orders, criminalising forced marriage and introducing a new offence of domestic abuse. We will strengthen victims’ rights further, with a new Victims’ Law that will enshrine key rights for victims. The previous government ring-fenced £40 million to VAWG services - £10 million per year, specifically for refuges. The government has committed to continuing that funding up to April 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Keeping Children Safe in Education (KCSIE) statutory guidance, issued by the Department for Education, outlines to schools and colleges their roles and responsibilities with regard to safeguarding their pupils. The department makes it clear that schools and colleges play a significant role in early identification of abuse and preventing concerns from escalating.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>KCSIE signposts school staff to specific forced marriage information and guidelines produced by the Forced Marriage Unit (FMU). This information provides an overview of forced marriage, together with FMU contact details for further information and advice.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>KCSIE also signposts schools to further information on faith abuse: the ‘National action plan to tackle child abuse linked to faith or belief’. This action plan serves to help raise awareness of the issue of child abuse linked to faith or belief, including honour based violence and forced marriage. The action plan encourages practical steps to be taken to prevent such abuse.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>KCSIE recognises that forced marriage and honour based violence are safeguarding concerns. The guidance makes clear that any concerns identified by staff should be raised and discussed with the school’s designated safeguarding lead and escalated to children’s social care as appropriate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Personal, Social, Health and Economic (PSHE) education, and Sex and Relationships Education (SRE) are curriculum subjects that may be used to raise pupil awareness of forced marriage and honour-based abuse. To support teaching in these areas, the PSHE Association has produced guidance for teaching about consent, covering the importance of building healthy relationships, as well as giving young people the confidence and knowledge about staying safe and respecting others. It also supports the government’s ‘This is Abuse’ campaign, which helps educate young people about damaging behaviours within relationships.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347624/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-10T16:15:44.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347624/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347624/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-06-01","Forced Marriage and Honour Based Violence: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to encourage schools to raise awareness of the risk of forced marriage and honour-based abuse, and of the availability of preventive measures.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347625","Home Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>The UK is a world leader in tackling forced marriage, and the Government is committed to ensuring that girls are not taken abroad for the purposes of forced marriage. That is why, during the previous Parliament, the Home Secretary made forced marriage a criminal offence, which included taking extra-territorial jurisdiction for forced marriage offences.</p><p>We recognise that strengthening the law is only part of the solution. The Government’s Forced Marriage Unit is leading efforts to combat this unacceptable activity both at home and abroad. Measures include providing support and advice to professionals and victims through a public helpline, with the Unit assisting in 1,267 cases in 2014. We are providing further direct support to professionals, including schools and the Crown Prosecution Service, through an extensive outreach and training programme and the publication of statutory multi-agency guidance in July 2014.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347625/answer",,,,,"HL170","2015-06-10T13:35:25.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347625/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347625/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-01","Forced Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that girls are not taken abroad for the purposes of forced marriage.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347626","Home Office","false","2015-06-10","<p>The UK is a world leader in tackling forced marriage, and the Government is committed to ensuring that girls are not taken abroad for the purposes of forced marriage. That is why, during the previous Parliament, the Home Secretary made forced marriage a criminal offence, which included taking extra-territorial jurisdiction for forced marriage offences.</p><p>We recognise that strengthening the law is only part of the solution. The Government’s Forced Marriage Unit is leading efforts to combat this unacceptable activity both at home and abroad. Measures include providing support and advice to professionals and victims through a public helpline, with the Unit assisting in 1,267 cases in 2014. We are providing further direct support to professionals, including schools and the Crown Prosecution Service, through an extensive outreach and training programme and the publication of statutory multi-agency guidance in July 2014.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347626/answer",,,,,"HL169","2015-06-10T13:35:26.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347626/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347626/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-01","Forced Marriage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures are in place to ensure that girls at risk of being taken abroad for the purpose of forced marriage are identified and assessed by professionals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347627","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-15","<p>The relevant provisions in the Deregulation Act 2015 will be implemented as soon as all the secondary legislation and guidance needed to make them work have been put in place.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347627/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-15T13:18:40.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347627/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347627/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-06-01","Rights of Way","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their timetable for implementing the provisions concerning footpaths and bridleways contained in the Deregulation Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347628","Home Office","false","2015-06-08","<p>Police horses make a valuable contribution in the prevention of crime and in maintaining public safety both locally and nationally. Mounted units have a long and proud tradition in law enforcement in the UK with operational decisions on their use and deployment the responsibility of Chief Constables.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347628/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T14:14:49.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347628/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347628/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-06-01","Police: Horses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the role played by horses in the policing of England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347629","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-06-15","<p>The Parliamentary Estates Directorate has links with Historic Royal Palaces and the occupied Royal Palaces. These bodies, along with the Government Historic Estates Unit and the National Trust, share knowledge gained from both the execution of works affecting the historic fabric of their buildings and the extensive research which precedes any such operation. The Restoration and Renewal Programme has had informal, off the record discussions with Historic Royal Palaces from time to time.</p>",,"Lord Sewel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347629/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-15T13:41:49.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347629/answer","Biography information for Lord Sewel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347629/answer",,,,,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-06-01","House of Lords: Repairs and Maintenance","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees whether there has been consultation with Historic Royal Palaces during the development of plans concerning the refurbishment of the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347630","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-08","<p>Figures published by BIS in <em>The Size and Performance of the UK Low Carbon Economy (March 2015) </em>[1] report show that in 2013 the renewable energy sector (including both renewable heat and renewable electricity) supported around 168,400 jobs [2] in total, an increase of 31,000 from 2010.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 details the number of jobs supported by the renewable energy sector, both directly and within the supply chain each year for 2010-2013. The equivalent information is not available for 2009 or 2014 or for the number of apprenticeships that have been created.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Number of jobs supported by the renewable energy sector in the UK</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Direct jobs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Supply chain/ indirect jobs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>2010</p></td><td><p>80,100</p></td><td><p>57,300</p></td><td><p>137,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>2011</p></td><td><p>89,600</p></td><td><p>64,000</p></td><td><p>153,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>2012</p></td><td><p>95,700</p></td><td><p>68,300</p></td><td><p>164,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p><p>2013</p></td><td><p>98,200</p></td><td><p>70,100</p></td><td><p>168,400</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416240/bis-15-206-size-and-performance-of-uk-low-carbon-economy.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416240/bis-15-206-size-and-performance-of-uk-low-carbon-economy.pdf</a></em></p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[2]</strong> </em><em> This figure is derived from the following sectors: offshore wind, solar PV, hydroelectric energy, onshore wind, marine, energy generation from waste, biomass equipment, geothermal, heat pumps, solar thermal, heat networks, heat recovery and ventilation and alternative fuels. Alternative fuels category includes jobs in both renewable and non-renewable energy sectors. </em></p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347630/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-08T13:03:19.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347630/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347630/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Renewable Energy: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many UK supply chain (a) jobs and (b) apprenticeships were created in the renewable energy sector in each year from 2009 to 2014.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347631","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>Any sale of this kind would be a commercial matter. Any owner would need to be fully compliant with all relevant regulatory requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347631/answer",,,,,"598","2015-06-04T15:34:01.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347631/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347631/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her Department's policy is on the potential sell-off by National Grid of its (a) gas distribution networks and (b) metering business.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347632","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>Any sale of this kind would be a commercial matter. Any owner would need to be fully compliant with all relevant regulatory requirements.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347632/answer",,,,,"597","2015-06-04T15:34:01.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347632/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347632/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on (a) local economies, (b) customer service and (c) safety of any sell-off of National Grid (i) gas distribution networks and (ii) metering business.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347633","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>No such discussions have taken place under this Government.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347633/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:34:28.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347633/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347633/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what meetings have taken place between representatives of her Department and National Grid about any sale of National Grid assets or businesses.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347634","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The UK Government welcomes responsible investment by both national and foreign investors in the UK’s energy infrastructure. This benefits our energy security, creates jobs, build skills, and helps grow our economy. All energy infrastructure in the UK must be operated in accordance with the relevant UK regulatory system.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347634/answer",,,,,"605","2015-06-04T16:30:15.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347634/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347634/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Energy: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what comparative assessment she has made of the benefits and disbenefits of (a) UK and (b) foreign ownership of energy infrastructure; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347635","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department has not estimated how many jobs will be created by investment in the planned Rampion wind farm.</p><p>The EON press release on Rampion states that during the planned 3 year offshore construction period up to 300 jobs will be created and local vessels utilised, with 40 roles being based at the project management facility in Newhaven Port. The press release also states that a workforce of up to 100 is expected to be needed for the onshore cable route and around a further 40 to 60 people at the onshore substation during onshore construction. Once the wind farm is commissioned and fully operational, it is envisaged that up to 65 full time permanent jobs will be created at the operations and maintenance base.</p><p>The Department, together with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, are working closely with EON to maximise UK benefit and ensure that UK supply chain companies have the opportunity to compete for contracts that have yet to be awarded.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347635/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:34:59.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347635/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347635/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many jobs will be created by investment in the planned Rampion wind farm; and what steps she is taking to ensure that UK supply chains benefit from such investment.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347636","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government is investing in the development of carbon capture and storage (CCS) in the UK. We are in negotiations to support up to two commercial scale CCS projects in the UK by making up to £1 billion available, together with operational support through a project specific Contract for Difference.</p><p>Together with the Scottish Government, we have recently committed, in principle, to provide £4.2 million to support Summit Power to undertake industrial research and development at their proposed CCS Caledonia Clean Energy Plant in Grangemouth Scotland. This is in addition to over £30 million of Government investment in CCS research and development since 2011.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347636/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:35:40.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347636/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347636/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what level of investment her Department plans to make in the development of carbon capture and storage.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347637","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>DECC does not hold this data.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347637/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T16:30:28.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347637/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347637/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Carbon Capture and Storage: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many (a) jobs and (b) apprenticeships were created in the development of carbon capture and storage in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347638","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>DECC does not hold figures on the proportion of coal used in UK electricity generation from imports.</p><p>However, in 2014, 34,174 thousand tonnes of steam coal (mainly used by coal-fired power stations) were imported into the UK, representing 89% of coal used for electricity generation (38,398 thousand tonnes).</p><p>The table below gives the breakdown of these imports by country:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Country of origin</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Steam Coal Imports</strong></p><p><strong>(thousand tonnes)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Share of all steam coal imports</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Russia</p></td><td><p>15,831</p></td><td><p>46.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Colombia</p></td><td><p>9,269</p></td><td><p>27.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>United States of America</p></td><td><p>7,687</p></td><td><p>22.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>European Union (1)</p></td><td><p>690</p></td><td><p>2.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Republic of South Africa</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>0.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Countries</p></td><td><p>569</p></td><td><p>1.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total all countries</strong></p></td><td><p>34,174</p></td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>(1) European Union includes non-EU routed through the Netherlands</em></p><p><em>Source: Energy Trends tables 2.1 and 2.4, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-section-2-energy-trends" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-section-2-energy-trends</a>.</em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347638/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:36:55.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347638/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347638/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Energy: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what proportion of coal used in UK energy generation is imported; and from which countries coal is imported.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347639","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department has not estimated the value of work accruing to UK manufacturing companies in each region from the development of the Rampion wind farm.</p><p>In November 2014 the Offshore Wind Industry Council adopted an industry-wide methodology for reporting on UK Content. This reporting helps industry hold itself to account on the commitment to reach 50% UK content, while charting progress and reporting to a wider public. This figure will show total UK content and break this down into the three main phases of development (devex), manufacture &amp; construction (capex) and operation (opex).</p><p>The first data will be submitted to RenewableUK by industry in summer 2015 for publication later in the year.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347639/answer",,,,,"603 ; 604","2015-06-04T15:37:28.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347639/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347639/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the value of work accruing to UK manufacturing companies in each region from the development of the Rampion wind farm.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347640","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department has not estimated the value of work accruing to UK manufacturing companies in each region from the development of the Rampion wind farm.</p><p>In November 2014 the Offshore Wind Industry Council adopted an industry-wide methodology for reporting on UK Content. This reporting helps industry hold itself to account on the commitment to reach 50% UK content, while charting progress and reporting to a wider public. This figure will show total UK content and break this down into the three main phases of development (devex), manufacture &amp; construction (capex) and operation (opex).</p><p>The first data will be submitted to RenewableUK by industry in summer 2015 for publication later in the year.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347640/answer",,,,,"602 ; 603","2015-06-04T15:37:28.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347640/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347640/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Renewable Energy: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential for northern cities to benefit from (a) Rampion wind farm and (b) other investment in renewable energy sources.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347641","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department has not estimated the value of work accruing to UK manufacturing companies in each region from the development of the Rampion wind farm.</p><p>In November 2014 the Offshore Wind Industry Council adopted an industry-wide methodology for reporting on UK Content. This reporting helps industry hold itself to account on the commitment to reach 50% UK content, while charting progress and reporting to a wider public. This figure will show total UK content and break this down into the three main phases of development (devex), manufacture &amp; construction (capex) and operation (opex).</p><p>The first data will be submitted to RenewableUK by industry in summer 2015 for publication later in the year.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347641/answer",,,,,"602 ; 604","2015-06-04T15:37:28.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347641/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347641/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment her Department has made of the potential benefit to the economy of each UK region of investment in the Rampion wind farm.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347642","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>The UK Government welcomes responsible investment by both national and foreign investors in the UK’s energy infrastructure. This benefits our energy security, creates jobs, build skills, and helps grow our economy. All energy infrastructure in the UK must be operated in accordance with the relevant UK regulatory system.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347642/answer",,,,,"600","2015-06-04T16:30:15.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347642/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347642/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Energy: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the benefits and disbenefits of UK ownership of energy infrastructure in relation to the security of energy supply.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347643","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-03","<p>The estimated number and proportion of households which are fuel poor in 2013 under the Low Income High Costs indicator in (a) England, (b) Yorkshire and the Humber (c) Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough constituency are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong><em>Number of households in fuel poverty (thousands)</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Proportion of households in fuel poverty within the area (%)</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>2,347</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sheffield Brightside and Hillsborough</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347643/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-03T16:01:30.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347643/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347643/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many people are classed as living in fuel poverty in (a) England, (b) Yorkshire and the Humber and (c) Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough constituency.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347644","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-06-04","<p>Fuel poverty is measured at the household level rather than the individual level and detailed data on the age of household occupants is not available at the sub-regional level. The table below shows the number and proportion of fuel poor households which contain at least one child under the age of 16 in (a) England and (b) Yorkshire and the Humber, in 2013.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong><em>Fuel poor households with at least one child under 16 (000s)</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Proportion of fuel poor households with at least one child under 16 (%)</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>1,064</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and Humberside</p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>52</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough the total number of households in fuel poverty was estimated to be six thousand, representing 14 per cent of all households in the region.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347644/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T09:18:47.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347644/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347644/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-06-01","Fuel Poverty: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many children live in households that are classed as being in fuel poverty in (a) England, (b) Yorkshire and the Humber and (c) Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough constituency.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347645","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-04","<p>Our current planning assumption is that the Defence budget for 2015-16 will be £34 billion. Decisions on spending for 2016-17 and beyond will be determined in the next spending review. However, the Government has committed to an annual 1% real terms increase in spending on Defence equipment over this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347645/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:57:37.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347645/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347645/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-06-01","Ministry of Defence: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of his Department's budget for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347646","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The total Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) settlement for the current financial year is £1.3 billion. After non-discretionary spend is removed, the FCO budget is around £700 million.</p><p>Like all Departments, we are preparing for the forthcoming Spending Review, which will determine the FCO's budget for 2016-17 and beyond.</p><p> </p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347646/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T15:54:27.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347646/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347646/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made his Department's budget for each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347647","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Government is deeply concerned about the proposals to demolish Bedouin villages in Israel. I visited the Khan al Ahmer Bedouin during my visit in October 2014 and saw at first hand the devestating impact resettlement plans had on the communities. Officials at our Embassy in Tel Aviv are monitoring the situation closely, including the case of the Um Il Hiran and Ateer. Embassy officials have been in contact with the Adalah Legal Centre who have continued to provide updates on the legal situation. They have also been in contact with other organisations that work within the Bedouin community, such as Itach-Maaki and The Arab-Jewish Center for Equality, Empowerment and Cooperation-Negev Institute for Strategies of Peace and Development, to best inform the UK’s lobbying of the Israeli authorities on this issue.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347647/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T13:27:55.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347647/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347647/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Israel: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effects of the proposed resettlement of Bedouin in Southern Israel on the peace process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>We recognise that more progress needs to be made on Tamil concerns as part of broader reconciliation in Sri Lanka.</p><p>President Sirisena has committed to introduce reforms to address inequalities faced by minority communities. These reforms are intended to improve access to education in Tamil; provide relief to displaced people; establish a democratic civil administration in the North and East; put a stop to racial and religious hatred; and to promote reconciliation between communities.</p><p> </p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347648/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T13:43:47.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347648/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347648/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Sri Lanka: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on official discrimination against Tamils in Sri Lanka; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347649","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The matter of accountability for alleged war crimes in Sri Lanka has been raised on a number of occasions with the new Sri Lankan government. I discussed the matter with the Sri Lankan government during my visit to Sri Lanka in January, and again with Foreign Minister Samaraweera during his visits to the UK in February and March. Separately the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Whitney (Mr Cameron), also discussed accountability with President Sirisena, and the Secretary of State for Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) further with Foreign Minister Samaraweera in March.</p><p>We were encouraged by the Sri Lankan government’s February commitment to co-operate with the Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights (OHCHR), and to establish a credible domestic process to investigate incidents of alleged war crimes and hold individuals to account. As Sri Lanka returns to the UN Human Rights Council in September for discussion it will be important for Sri Lanka to show real progress on this important matter.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347649/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T13:45:54.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347649/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347649/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-06-01","Sri Lanka: War Crimes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has received from the government of Sri Lanka about allegations of war crimes in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347650","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The planned completion for the work to install a rigid concrete barrier is 7 September 2015.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347650/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T09:22:07.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347650/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347650/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","M1","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the roadworks on the M1 between junctions 15 and 19 will be completed.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347651","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The planned expenditure for this phase of works is £62.5 million. Actual costs can only be determined once the works are completed and final accounts calculated.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The M1 J19 to 15 is replacing the existing steel barrier with a new concrete barrier. This includes removal of the existing steel central reserve barrier and all the existing lighting columns as these are no longer required. We have also undertaken a number of maintenance repairs to bridge piers that sit within the central reserve negating the need for any follow on scheme to carry these out. These works will have a significant reduction in the future maintenance needs for the central reserve as well as assisting in the preparation for the M1 J19-16 Smart Motorway All Lane Running (SM ALR) project that is currently in development.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347651/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T09:25:03.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347651/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347651/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","M1","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse is of the roadworks taking place on the M1 between junctions 15 and 19.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347652","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>There have been no discussions on the A483 upgrade. Progress on the A55/A483 pinch point scheme was discussed with Highways England in February 2015. The outcome of the discussion was that the completion date for the scheme would be rescheduled to 10 May 2015, as set out in the answer of 2 March (UIN 225319). The scheme completion date has since been rescheduled to 28 June 2015.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347652/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T08:46:48.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347652/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347652/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he last discussed the progress of the A483 upgrade with Highways England; and what the outcome of that discussion was.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347653","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>The Secretary of State has not received representations.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347653/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T08:49:44.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347653/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347653/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A55: A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has received from local (a) authorities and (b) businesses on delays to the A55/A483 upgrade project.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347654","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>An accurate estimate of the costs can only be determined when the scheme is completed and the final accounts calculated.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347654/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T08:52:26.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347654/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347654/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A55: A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an estimate of the cost of the delays to the A55/A483 upgrade project to (a) the public purse and (b) businesses within 10 miles of the project.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347655","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>I and my Ministerial colleagues have regular discussions with HM Treasury and Department for Business, Innovation and Skills Ministers, though there has been no specific discussion on this issue.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347655/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T08:56:46.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347655/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347655/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A55: A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had about the economic effect of the delays to the A55/A483 upgrade project on the area with (a) the Chancellor of the Exchequer and (b) the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347656","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>I am satisfied that Highways England has provided information of the appropriate quality for motorists. Prior to construction work starting, a public exhibition was held on 5 September 2014, with a further public exhibition on 11 December 2014.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout the project, other information has been provided for motorists via:</p><p> </p><p>· Local radio messages, live radio interviews advising motorists to use alternative routes;</p><p> </p><p>· On-site visitor centre;</p><p> </p><p>· Temporary roadside signs;</p><p> </p><p>· Portable electronic message signs on the M56 Motorway just before the junction with the M53 (the M53 continues as the A55);</p><p> </p><p>· Press releases and Twitter feed updates.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347656/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T09:00:13.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347656/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347656/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A55: A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he is satisfied with the quality of the information that his Department has given to motorists during the A55/A483 upgrade project.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347657","Department for Transport","false","2015-06-09","<p>Highways England has rescheduled the scheme completion date to 28 June 2015 after further problems were uncovered during the strengthening works to the western bridge which required revised designs and approvals which had subsequent impacts on the available work areas resulting in an overall programme delay.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347657/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-09T09:03:34.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347657/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347657/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-06-01","A483","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 25 February 2015 to Question 225319, for what reasons the A483 upgrade project missed its extended deadline.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347658","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are continuing to discuss with their staff the locations of the future Regional Centres. They have however, told them how in-principle decisions will be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For Wales, HMRC has told staff that it believes that Cardiff is the most suitable location for a future Regional Centre in Wales, since it is already the biggest HMRC location in the country. However, no decisions have yet been made on the precise location or timing of a new HMRC Regional Centre in Cardiff or the nature and timing of impacts on other HMRC locations in Wales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October 2014, HMRC shared the main elements of the Building our Future vision with MPs and Assembly Members and HMRC has committed to keeping MPs and Assembly Members informed of the outcomes of these conversations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All HMRC staff members are invited to participate in Building our Future events and staff choose which event and location they attend. Over 85% of Wrexham staff attended the last set of events.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347658/answer",,,,,"650 ; 651 ; 652","2015-06-08T14:41:49.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347658/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347658/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Revenue and Customs: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 23 March 2015 to Question 228104, what his Department's current plans are for reorganisation of HM Revenue and Customs in Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347659","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are continuing to discuss with their staff the locations of the future Regional Centres. They have however, told them how in-principle decisions will be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For Wales, HMRC has told staff that it believes that Cardiff is the most suitable location for a future Regional Centre in Wales, since it is already the biggest HMRC location in the country. However, no decisions have yet been made on the precise location or timing of a new HMRC Regional Centre in Cardiff or the nature and timing of impacts on other HMRC locations in Wales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October 2014, HMRC shared the main elements of the Building our Future vision with MPs and Assembly Members and HMRC has committed to keeping MPs and Assembly Members informed of the outcomes of these conversations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All HMRC staff members are invited to participate in Building our Future events and staff choose which event and location they attend. Over 85% of Wrexham staff attended the last set of events.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347659/answer",,,,,"631 ; 651 ; 652","2015-06-08T14:41:49.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347659/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347659/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Revenue and Customs: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 23 March 2015 to Question 228104, what progress his Department has made on the consultation process Building our Future, on HM Revenue and Customs reorganisation.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347660","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are continuing to discuss with their staff the locations of the future Regional Centres. They have however, told them how in-principle decisions will be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For Wales, HMRC has told staff that it believes that Cardiff is the most suitable location for a future Regional Centre in Wales, since it is already the biggest HMRC location in the country. However, no decisions have yet been made on the precise location or timing of a new HMRC Regional Centre in Cardiff or the nature and timing of impacts on other HMRC locations in Wales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October 2014, HMRC shared the main elements of the Building our Future vision with MPs and Assembly Members and HMRC has committed to keeping MPs and Assembly Members informed of the outcomes of these conversations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All HMRC staff members are invited to participate in Building our Future events and staff choose which event and location they attend. Over 85% of Wrexham staff attended the last set of events.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347660/answer",,,,,"631 ; 650 ; 652","2015-06-08T14:41:49.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347660/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347660/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Revenue and Customs: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 23 March 2015 to Question 228104, what the outcomes have been of the conversations his Department has had with hon. Members and Welsh Assembly Members on HM Revenue and Customs reorganisation since October 2014.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347661","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-08","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are continuing to discuss with their staff the locations of the future Regional Centres. They have however, told them how in-principle decisions will be made.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For Wales, HMRC has told staff that it believes that Cardiff is the most suitable location for a future Regional Centre in Wales, since it is already the biggest HMRC location in the country. However, no decisions have yet been made on the precise location or timing of a new HMRC Regional Centre in Cardiff or the nature and timing of impacts on other HMRC locations in Wales.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In October 2014, HMRC shared the main elements of the Building our Future vision with MPs and Assembly Members and HMRC has committed to keeping MPs and Assembly Members informed of the outcomes of these conversations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All HMRC staff members are invited to participate in Building our Future events and staff choose which event and location they attend. Over 85% of Wrexham staff attended the last set of events.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347661/answer",,,,,"631 ; 650 ; 651","2015-06-08T14:41:49.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347661/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347661/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Revenue and Customs: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 23 March 2015 to Question 228104, on which occasions he or other representatives of his Department met staff from the Wrexham HM Revenue and Customs office to discuss the future of that office; and what the outcomes were of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347663","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department for Transport is responsible for reviewing business cases for transport infrastructure projects.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347663/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T14:31:15.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347663/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347663/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Garden Bridge","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what process his Department undertook to scrutinise the business case for the proposed Garden Bridge project.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347664","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Department for Transport is responsible for reviewing business cases for transport infrastructure projects. The Garden Bridge business case included alternative locations for the project.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347664/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T14:16:53.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347664/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347664/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Garden Bridge","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential benefits of a new Thames pedestrian bridge at alternative locations to that of the proposed Garden Bridge project.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347665","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>HM Treasury has no record of the Chancellor meeting with Joanna Lumley to discuss the Garden Bridge in any of the last three years.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347665/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T14:17:44.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347665/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347665/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Garden Bridge","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what dates he has met Joanna Lumley to discuss the proposed Garden Bridge project in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347666","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>I can confirm that Treasury officials have not spoken to Joanna Lumley about the Garden Bridge project in any of the last three years.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347666/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T14:24:24.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347666/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347666/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-06-01","Garden Bridge","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what dates officials in his Department have met Joanna Lumley to discuss the proposed Garden Bridge project in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347667","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-04","<p>The UK Government remains strongly committed to completing an ambitious EU-US Free Trade Agreement (EU-US FTA), also known as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP). We are pressing for an agreement under the current US Administration, which means we need to see tangible progress by end-2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following the most recent negotiating round which took place between 20 and 24 April in New York, there continues to be good progress on the technical work which would underpin the final deal. However, in order to reach an agreement in principle this year, the European Commission, EU Member States and the US will need to work closely together over the coming months. The next negotiating round is due to take place in July.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347667/answer",,,,,,"2015-06-04T12:32:08.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347667/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347667/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-06-01","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he expects the TTIP negotiations between the EU and the US to be concluded.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","657"
